my mother's life is guided
by a large number of aphorisms.

78
00:04:05,245 --> 00:04:08,214
Sayings.
Like, for example...

79
00:04:08,314 --> 00:04:10,248
<i>[Mrs. Devereaux]</i>
<i>What you do while you're in a room...</i>

80
00:04:10,350 --> 00:04:12,409
- You don't wanna go in there.
- <i>is never as important as how</i>
<i>you enter or leave it.</i>

81
00:04:12,518 --> 00:04:15,487
- [Screams]
- Please. Don't get up.

82
00:04:15,588 --> 00:04:19,319
- This isn't what it looks like.
- Really? Well, what does it look like, child?

83
00:04:19,425 --> 00:04:22,326
- Danny!
- Of course it's what it looks like, Sherry.

84
00:04:22,428 --> 00:04:25,158
- My wife's not an idiot, for Christ's sake.
- <i>Thank you, darling.</i>

85
00:04:25,265 --> 00:04:28,132
That's the nicest thing
you've said to me all year.

86
00:04:28,234 --> 00:04:30,634
Here. Let me help you.

87
00:04:30,737 --> 00:04:33,262
<i>You know, you really</i>
<i>shouldn't wear this color.</i>

88
00:04:33,373 --> 00:04:35,705
It makes you look like a tramp.

89
00:04:35,808 --> 00:04:38,743
What am I saying?
You are a tramp.

90
00:04:38,845 --> 00:04:42,337
Hey. What are you doin'
with that suitcase?

91
00:04:42,448 --> 00:04:45,144
- I'm leaving you.
- Oh, Christ, honey.

92
00:04:45,251 --> 00:04:48,379
Come on. You know
you're not gonna leave me.

93
00:04:48,488 --> 00:04:51,753
Never contradict a woman
while you're in your underwear.

94
00:04:51,858 --> 00:04:54,486
It puts you at a great disadvantage.

95
00:04:54,594 --> 00:04:57,927
I'm-I'm-I'm sorry. Baby, I am.
You know I do these crazy things.

96
00:04:58,031 --> 00:05:01,091
But they don't mean anything.
No offense, Sherry. Sherry?

97
00:05:01,200 --> 00:05:04,431
Oh, come on now, honey.
Be realistic.

98
00:05:04,537 --> 00:05:07,529
W-Where would you go?
What would you do?

99
00:05:07,640 --> 00:05:12,009
- Where's my passport?
- Oh, hell. Go on then. Leave me.

100
00:05:12,111 --> 00:05:14,978
I don't need you around here anyway. All
you do is hold me back and spend my money.

101
00:05:15,081 --> 00:05:18,517
- And everybody knows that.
- What a relief for you then.

102
00:05:18,618 --> 00:05:20,916
- Well, what about the boys?
- <i>Boys?</i>

103
00:05:21,020 --> 00:05:25,548
- Yeah. George, Robbie. The boys.
You remember them?
- Where are they?

104
00:05:25,658 --> 00:05:27,922
- They're at school, Miss Devereaux.
- Why?

105
00:05:28,027 --> 00:05:31,519
- I'm going to take them with me.
- And do what?

106
00:05:31,631 --> 00:05:33,531
- Raise them.
- You?

107
00:05:33,633 --> 00:05:36,500
Well, you don't think I'm leaving them here
with the likes of you, do you?

108
00:05:36,602 --> 00:05:39,070
Give me a break.
You're a lousy mother.

109
00:05:39,172 --> 00:05:40,901
- I love my children.
- So what?

110
00:05:41,007 --> 00:05:44,875
I love my kids, and I'm shit for a father.

111
00:05:44,977 --> 00:05:46,535
- Bernice?
- <i>Yes, ma'am?</i>

112
00:05:46,646 --> 00:05:49,308
Am I a lousy mother?

113
00:05:49,415 --> 00:05:52,043
It's not my place to say, Miss Devereaux.

114
00:05:52,151 --> 00:05:54,051
[Softly]
But if you wanna know the God's honest...

115
00:05:54,153 --> 00:05:55,643
- There.
- Aw, shit.

116
00:05:55,755 --> 00:05:59,418
Go on, then.
Take the damn kids. What do I care?

117
00:06:01,227 --> 00:06:03,718
<i>[Elevator Whirring]</i>

118
00:06:13,973 --> 00:06:16,874
[Sighs]

119
00:06:19,779 --> 00:06:22,009
<i>[Elevator Bell Dings]</i>

120
00:06:27,019 --> 00:06:29,647
- <i>[Elevator Doors Close]</i>
- <i>[Narrating] Ten minutes later...</i>

121
00:06:29,756 --> 00:06:32,953
- <i>my mother took my brother and me out of school.</i>
- Shit.

122
00:06:33,059 --> 00:06:36,790
I'm sorry, Mrs. Devereaux, but your boys
don't attend this school anymore.

123
00:06:36,896 --> 00:06:40,696
Of course they don't.
[Chuckles]

124
00:06:40,800 --> 00:06:43,860
I'm sorry, Mr. Connors.
I'm just very upset.

125
00:06:43,970 --> 00:06:45,767
- <i>They go to...</i>
- Radford.

126
00:06:45,872 --> 00:06:48,340
Radford. Of course.

127
00:06:48,441 --> 00:06:50,602
They go to Radford.

128
00:06:55,648 --> 00:06:57,707
Where is Radford?

129
00:06:57,817 --> 00:07:01,378
<i>[Narrating] My brother Robbie was playing</i>
<i>Lady Macbeth in the Scottish play.</i>

130
00:07:01,487 --> 00:07:05,253
It is so nice to see that
there are still some gentlemen left.

131
00:07:05,358 --> 00:07:07,326
Thank you.

132
00:07:08,428 --> 00:07:10,328
<i>[Man]</i>
<i>He was playing Lady Macbeth?</i>

133
00:07:10,430 --> 00:07:13,922
In Shakespeare's time,
all the women's roles were played by men.

134
00:07:14,033 --> 00:07:16,558
Right. I knew that.

135
00:07:17,670 --> 00:07:20,798
That's all the cash there is in here,
Mrs. Devereaux.

136
00:07:20,907 --> 00:07:23,307
- And all the jewelry.
- Of course.

137
00:07:24,777 --> 00:07:26,677
What's in that cloth there?

138
00:07:28,681 --> 00:07:31,241
- Oh.
- I'll take that too.

139
00:07:31,350 --> 00:07:33,648
Will that be all, Mrs. Devereaux?

140
00:07:37,056 --> 00:07:39,820
That will be all. Thank you.

141
00:07:43,963 --> 00:07:46,022
George, darling.

142
00:07:46,132 --> 00:07:50,034
I want you to take this money
and go and buy us an automobile.

143
00:07:50,136 --> 00:07:52,468
A car? Why? Where's Dad?

144
00:07:52,572 --> 00:07:55,507
First things first.
We need a car.

145
00:07:55,608 --> 00:07:58,406
- Well, what kind of car?
- What kind would you like?

146
00:07:58,511 --> 00:08:00,638
- I don't want a car.
- A Jaguar.

147
00:08:00,746 --> 00:08:03,044
Admirable taste as always, darling.

148
00:08:03,149 --> 00:08:05,515
But we need something more practical.

149
00:08:05,618 --> 00:08:09,520
- A Chevy?
- Perhaps not that practical.

150
00:08:09,622 --> 00:08:11,715
So here I am,
and that's the car I want.

151
00:08:11,824 --> 00:08:13,689
It's not as easy as that, son.

152
00:08:13,793 --> 00:08:18,059
- Is there a problem, George?
- Have a seat, Mrs. Devereaux.

153
00:08:18,164 --> 00:08:20,724
Well, thank you, Fred.

154
00:08:20,833 --> 00:08:23,324
- May I call you Fred?
- By all means.

155
00:08:23,436 --> 00:08:25,336
Well, how much is the car we want?

156
00:08:25,438 --> 00:08:27,338
It's, uh, 3,500, ma'am.

157
00:08:27,440 --> 00:08:31,137
- Give it to the nice man, George.
- That's not how you do it, Mom.

158
00:08:31,244 --> 00:08:34,042
- That's not how you do what?
- Your son means that...

159
00:08:34,146 --> 00:08:37,582
you offer me less than that,
and then we bargain.

160
00:08:37,683 --> 00:08:41,813
All right. $1,000.

161
00:08:41,921 --> 00:08:44,913
- [Chuckling]
- This is so much fun.

162
00:08:45,024 --> 00:08:47,049
What?

163
00:08:47,159 --> 00:08:49,821
<i>It's a little low, Mom.</i>

164
00:08:49,929 --> 00:08:52,989
- <i>Offer me, say, 2,500.</i>
- All right, then.

165
00:08:53,099 --> 00:08:55,567
2,500.

166
00:08:55,668 --> 00:08:58,569
- No.
- <i>What do you mean, no?</i>

167
00:08:58,671 --> 00:09:00,434
You just said, "Offer me 2,500."

168
00:09:00,540 --> 00:09:05,568
I can let you have it for 33, Mrs. Devereaux,
but that's as low as I can go.

169
00:09:05,678 --> 00:09:07,612
2,700.

170
00:09:07,713 --> 00:09:09,374
3,275.

171
00:09:09,482 --> 00:09:14,784
2,950, Fred, or we're out of here
faster than a cat in a rainstorm.

172
00:09:14,887 --> 00:09:18,015
- Huh?
- <i>[George] What about Dad?</i>

173
00:09:18,124 --> 00:09:20,149
What does he have to say about all this?

174
00:09:20,259 --> 00:09:24,696
Your father has betrayed us,
and I never wanna hear his name again.

175
00:09:24,797 --> 00:09:26,697
What about marrying my father again?

176
00:09:26,799 --> 00:09:29,563
Once was an adventure.
Twice would be a perversion.

177
00:09:29,669 --> 00:09:33,105
Look, you can't just take a kid
away from his father like this.

178
00:09:33,205 --> 00:09:35,799
Ask any psychiatrist.
A boy needs his father's influence.

179
00:09:35,908 --> 00:09:40,277
- That is what the telephone is for.
- I'm not going.

180
00:09:40,379 --> 00:09:43,576
- Well, who's gonna drive the car?
- Robbie can drive.

181
00:09:43,683 --> 00:09:45,480
Robbie doesn't have
the personality for driving.

182
00:09:45,585 --> 00:09:48,782
- I'm too sensitive.
- You're too full of shit is what you are.

183
00:09:48,888 --> 00:09:51,482
- George!
- Then you drive it.

184
00:09:51,591 --> 00:09:53,582
It would not be appropriate
for me to drive it.

185
00:09:53,693 --> 00:09:56,218
It's 1953, Mom.
Women vote now.

186
00:09:56,329 --> 00:09:58,820
They smoke. They even
go to the bathroom by themselves.

187
00:09:58,931 --> 00:10:01,456
You're becoming very crude, darling.

188
00:10:01,567 --> 00:10:03,467
Your father's influence, no doubt.

189
00:10:05,438 --> 00:10:07,338
Nice car.

190
00:10:08,741 --> 00:10:11,437
<i>The only reason why I'm giving in...</i>

191
00:10:11,544 --> 00:10:15,446
is because I know that
we'll be back here in a week.

192
00:10:15,548 --> 00:10:18,039
It's time for your boy's medicine, ma'am.

193
00:10:18,150 --> 00:10:21,278
- Bernice has your medicine, George. Take it.
- <i>It's not my medicine.</i>

194
00:10:21,387 --> 00:10:23,287
I do not care whose medicine it is.

195
00:10:23,389 --> 00:10:26,085
Just one of you take it,
and let's get out of here.

196
00:10:26,192 --> 00:10:28,160
Good-bye, Bernice.

197
00:10:28,260 --> 00:10:31,752
<i>I'll miss you.</i>
<i>Any parting words of advice for us?</i>

198
00:10:31,864 --> 00:10:34,765
Yeah. Take the parking brake off.

199
00:10:39,105 --> 00:10:41,198
- <i>[Gears Grinding]</i>
- <i>[Robbie] George! George!</i>

200
00:10:41,307 --> 00:10:44,708
- Please don't get us killed.
- [Tires Screeching]

201
00:10:46,812 --> 00:10:49,372
<i>[Narrating] My mother was</i>
<i>determined to teach my father a lesson...</i>

202
00:10:49,482 --> 00:10:51,950
<i>even if it meant</i>
<i>killing us all in the process.</i>

203
00:10:52,051 --> 00:10:55,646
<i>With that in mind, she told us</i>
<i>to drive around the city for an hour...</i>

204
00:10:55,755 --> 00:10:58,952
<i>so she could teach me everything</i>
<i>she knew about driving a car...</i>

205
00:10:59,058 --> 00:11:01,185
- <i>which wasn't much.</i>
- <i>[Brakes Screech]</i>

206
00:11:01,293 --> 00:11:03,193
George, I almost stabbed myself.

207
00:11:03,295 --> 00:11:05,354
- You wanna drive?
- That was a lovely stop.

208
00:11:05,464 --> 00:11:08,695
You're a natural, darling.
Well, I think we're ready to go.

209
00:11:08,801 --> 00:11:11,167
- Anywhere in particular?
- Boston.

210
00:11:11,270 --> 00:11:12,498
- Boston?
- Mm-hmm.

211
00:11:12,605 --> 00:11:16,541
- For how long?
- Well, with a little luck, forever.

212
00:11:16,642 --> 00:11:18,701
What are we going to do in Boston?

213
00:11:18,811 --> 00:11:20,711
We're gonna start a new life.

214
00:11:20,813 --> 00:11:25,409
We are going to have fun, that's what.
My dear friend Julie Harper lives there.

215
00:11:25,518 --> 00:11:29,352
- Bette Davis was born in Boston.
- Boston is a very elegant city.

216
00:11:29,455 --> 00:11:31,650
It's full of museums and universities.

217
00:11:31,757 --> 00:11:33,850
- Tea parties.
- Precisely.

218
00:11:33,959 --> 00:11:36,223
Accelerate, darling.

219
00:11:36,328 --> 00:11:40,697
- Put the pedal to the metal, George.
- Whoa, whoa, whoa.

220
00:11:40,800 --> 00:11:43,428
- What did you just do?
- I was checking the rear view mirror.

221
00:11:43,536 --> 00:11:47,131
Oh. Never, never look
in the rear view mirror, darling.

222
00:11:47,239 --> 00:11:49,207
It makes no difference what's behind you.

223
00:11:49,308 --> 00:11:51,708
I don't even know why
they put those up there.

224
00:11:51,811 --> 00:11:54,177
Just look where you're going
and pretend that that's not even there.

225
00:11:54,280 --> 00:11:56,441
- Understood?
- Yes, ma'am.

226
00:11:56,549 --> 00:11:58,414
Now go.

227
00:12:05,057 --> 00:12:07,252
<i>[Narrating] The whole drive up</i>
<i>to Boston, my mother and Robbie...</i>

228
00:12:07,359 --> 00:12:09,327
<i>planned their upcoming adventures.</i>

229
00:12:09,428 --> 00:12:12,192
<i>Around Hartford, her euphoria</i>
<i>was sounding a little forced.</i>

230
00:12:12,298 --> 00:12:14,493
<i>It made me think.</i>
<i>By the time we got to Boston...</i>

231
00:12:14,600 --> 00:12:17,160
<i>she'd proclaim this was all</i>
<i>a big misunderstanding...</i>

232
00:12:17,269 --> 00:12:20,204
<i>and tell me to turn around</i>
<i>and drive us back to New York.</i>

233
00:12:20,306 --> 00:12:22,206
<i>But she didn't.</i>

234
00:12:22,308 --> 00:12:25,243
We'll stay here until
Julie returns from her cruise.

235
00:12:25,344 --> 00:12:28,108
- Mom, isn't this place a little...
- Isn't it a little what?

236
00:12:28,214 --> 00:12:30,409
Well, don't you think that
we should be saving our money?

237
00:12:30,516 --> 00:12:34,850
Certainly not.
What an unpleasant thought.

238
00:12:34,954 --> 00:12:36,945
- Sorry. I'm sorry. Oh!
- Oh, my goodness.

239
00:12:37,056 --> 00:12:40,025
- Are you okay?
- I'm very sorry.

240
00:12:40,126 --> 00:12:42,026
- Oh, my goodness. Ann Devereaux.
- Wallace...

241
00:12:42,128 --> 00:12:44,562
- Ann Devereaux.
- Wallace McCallister!

242
00:12:44,663 --> 00:12:47,461
<i>[Ann] Wally's an old beau of mine,</i>
<i>and he's divorced.</i>

243
00:12:47,566 --> 00:12:49,431
He once asked me to marry him.

244
00:12:49,535 --> 00:12:53,733
<i>He tried to kill himself when I turned</i>
<i>him down. Unsuccessfully, of course.</i>

245
00:12:53,839 --> 00:12:56,000
Great. He deserves another chance.

246
00:12:56,108 --> 00:12:59,373
Well, if that's the way you wanna put it.

247
00:12:59,478 --> 00:13:01,776
So, is this the look
we're going for, Robbie?

248
00:13:01,881 --> 00:13:06,181
I'm trying to find you a balance between
Dorothy Malone and Donna Reed.

249
00:13:06,285 --> 00:13:09,277
- Try this one.
- I'm completely in your hands, darling.

250
00:13:09,388 --> 00:13:13,119
- You're like some predator.
- I'm merely having dinner with an old friend.

251
00:13:13,225 --> 00:13:15,750
Like the angler fish we studied in biology.

252
00:13:15,861 --> 00:13:18,489
Never compare a woman to a fish, George...

253
00:13:18,597 --> 00:13:22,465
- or anything with scales for that matter.
- Here. Try these.

254
00:13:22,568 --> 00:13:24,763
[Gasps]
They're perfect.

255
00:13:26,338 --> 00:13:29,569
We're newcomers here, and Wallace
is a well-respected gentleman...

256
00:13:29,675 --> 00:13:32,644
whose friendship will help
establish us in the community.

257
00:13:32,745 --> 00:13:36,112
I got a feeling this is all gonna
come flying right back in your face.

258
00:13:36,215 --> 00:13:39,844
<i>Nonsense.</i>
<i>Everything works out for the best.</i>

259
00:13:39,952 --> 00:13:41,920
Always.

260
00:13:48,928 --> 00:13:52,227
- <i>[Door Closes]</i>
- What?

261
00:13:52,331 --> 00:13:54,822
- [Laughing]
- <i># #[Piano]</i>

262
00:13:56,569 --> 00:13:59,629
Wallace, you haven't changed a bit.

263
00:13:59,738 --> 00:14:01,000
[Snickering]

264
00:14:07,880 --> 00:14:09,848
Thank you.

265
00:14:11,650 --> 00:14:15,108
[Groans]
Goddamn, Ann.

266
00:14:15,221 --> 00:14:17,712
Why can't we just go back...

267
00:14:17,823 --> 00:14:20,314
to the way everything was, huh?

268
00:14:20,426 --> 00:14:23,725
Well, sometimes,
fate offers us a second chance.

269
00:14:23,829 --> 00:14:26,229
- <i>[Liquid Pouring]</i>
- Mm-hmm.

270
00:14:32,838 --> 00:14:35,705
<i>Wallace, is something wrong?</i>

271
00:14:35,808 --> 00:14:37,776
Um...

272
00:14:42,248 --> 00:14:44,216
Things are, um...

273
00:14:49,755 --> 00:14:53,122
Things are bad for me, Ann.
They're bad.

274
00:14:53,225 --> 00:14:58,629
Well, divorce is a terrible experience.

275
00:14:58,731 --> 00:15:01,791
But sometimes, good things can come from...
from trials like ours.

276
00:15:01,901 --> 00:15:06,531
I'm not talking about divorce.
I'm talking about... my business.

277
00:15:06,639 --> 00:15:09,369
- Oh, your business.
- Yeah.

278
00:15:09,475 --> 00:15:14,071
I've had a setback,
and-and-and l-I need cash.

279
00:15:14,179 --> 00:15:17,637
Lots of cash, and fast.

280
00:15:19,084 --> 00:15:22,076
[Scoffs]
Lower your voice, Wallace.

281
00:15:25,591 --> 00:15:27,991
It's why I wanted to see you tonight.

282
00:15:29,929 --> 00:15:32,921
Can you lend me some money?

283
00:15:33,032 --> 00:15:35,125
Can I what?

284
00:15:35,234 --> 00:15:36,792
75,000 would do it.

285
00:15:36,902 --> 00:15:39,097
- Dollars?
- All right, 50.

286
00:15:39,204 --> 00:15:44,506
Fifty. And I will get it back to you
by the end of the month, I swear to God.

287
00:15:44,610 --> 00:15:48,137
It's not appropriate for you
to solicit money from me.

288
00:15:48,247 --> 00:15:51,444
Appropriate? Appropriate my ass!

289
00:15:51,550 --> 00:15:55,919
<i>I am broke, babe!</i>
<i>The wolves are circlin'.</i>

290
00:15:56,021 --> 00:15:58,922
They're standin' in line
waitin' to take chunks out of my ass...

291
00:15:59,024 --> 00:16:01,686
bigger than that flank steak you just had!

292
00:16:01,794 --> 00:16:05,195
- <i>[Slams Fist On Table]</i>
- Sorry. I'm sorry.

293
00:16:05,297 --> 00:16:09,199
Please excuse me while I powder my nose.

294
00:16:10,569 --> 00:16:12,901
Okay.

295
00:16:13,005 --> 00:16:16,168
[Sniffling]

296
00:16:20,045 --> 00:16:22,013
[Sighs]

297
00:16:29,188 --> 00:16:33,522
Everything will work out for the best,
George Devereaux.

298
00:16:33,625 --> 00:16:35,183
You'll see.

299
00:17:06,625 --> 00:17:10,459
<i>It's not our policy to extend credit</i>
<i>to patrons we do not know.</i>

300
00:17:10,562 --> 00:17:15,693
Oh. Well, is it your policy for your patrons
to be robbed in plain sight?

301
00:17:15,801 --> 00:17:18,429
- Madam, please.
- Listen, I am the victim here.

302
00:17:18,537 --> 00:17:22,029
I returned from the ladies' room
to find that my purse has been ransacked.

303
00:17:22,141 --> 00:17:25,668
Madam, all I know is that
someone needs to pay for this meal.

304
00:17:25,778 --> 00:17:28,042
Trust me, I already have.

305
00:17:28,147 --> 00:17:31,913
Ma'am? May I be of assistance?

306
00:17:32,017 --> 00:17:34,508
Well, who are you, cavalry?

307
00:17:34,620 --> 00:17:37,555
Henry, I'll take care of that.
Harlan.

308
00:17:37,656 --> 00:17:39,556
Harlan Williams.

309
00:17:39,658 --> 00:17:41,888
We met at Julie Harper's
Christmas party last year.

310
00:17:41,994 --> 00:17:45,430
Yes, of course. Harlan.
Well, Colonel.

311
00:17:45,531 --> 00:17:47,863
<i>[George]</i>
<i>Why does he wear that uniform all the time?</i>

312
00:17:47,966 --> 00:17:51,265
<i>Hasn't anyone told him the war is over,</i>
<i>for Christ's sake?</i>

313
00:17:51,370 --> 00:17:53,270
<i>[Robbie]</i>
<i>Now that he and Mom are engaged...</i>

314
00:17:53,372 --> 00:17:55,272
<i>I bet he sends us off to military school.</i>

315
00:17:55,374 --> 00:17:58,741
<i>[George] I hate the way he calls me</i>
<i>Georgie boy all the time.</i>

316
00:17:58,844 --> 00:18:01,074
<i>I hate the way he keeps</i>
<i>slapping me on the back...</i>

317
00:18:01,180 --> 00:18:04,581
<i>like he's trying to dislodge a piece of meat</i>
<i>from my throat or something.</i>

318
00:18:04,683 --> 00:18:07,413
If he touches my hair one more time,
I'm gonna kill him.

319
00:18:07,519 --> 00:18:11,114
Holden Caulfield would tell him
what he really thought about him.

320
00:18:11,223 --> 00:18:13,418
Holden hates phonies more than anything.

321
00:18:13,525 --> 00:18:16,050
Holden Caulfield
is a fictional character, George.

322
00:18:17,396 --> 00:18:20,229
You ever think about goin' back to Dad?

323
00:18:20,332 --> 00:18:22,562
He's your father, not mine.

324
00:18:22,668 --> 00:18:25,466
What was your father like?

325
00:18:25,571 --> 00:18:30,008
I saw a picture of him once.
His pants were too short.

326
00:18:30,109 --> 00:18:32,839
You think Mom is crazy?

327
00:18:35,214 --> 00:18:38,945
I can't tell.
She's the only one I've had.

328
00:18:40,352 --> 00:18:42,786
<i>Every time there's a picture</i>
<i>of a Communist in the school...</i>

329
00:18:42,888 --> 00:18:45,413
he's always wearing a wool cap
and driving a tractor.

330
00:18:45,524 --> 00:18:48,960
That's 'cause Stalin
killed all the designers.

331
00:18:49,061 --> 00:18:52,258
That's why we're fighting
Communism, boys.

332
00:18:52,364 --> 00:18:55,026
Because we're a country
that's founded on individualism.

333
00:18:55,134 --> 00:18:57,659
- Right, George?
- Yes, sir.

334
00:18:57,769 --> 00:19:02,263
Hell, if the Commies did take over,
everybody would be wearing the same clothes.

335
00:19:02,374 --> 00:19:05,172
Every street would have
the same exact stores...

336
00:19:05,277 --> 00:19:07,973
no matter which town you went to,
each the same as the next.

337
00:19:09,948 --> 00:19:11,848
That's why our boys
are fighting and dying...

338
00:19:11,950 --> 00:19:13,918
so that doesn't happen.

339
00:19:15,754 --> 00:19:17,187
[Whispering]

340
00:19:17,289 --> 00:19:19,018
[Clears Throat]

341
00:19:19,124 --> 00:19:21,217
[Both Snickering]

342
00:19:21,326 --> 00:19:23,226
Did I say something funny, George?

343
00:19:23,328 --> 00:19:25,125
It was nothing, sir.

344
00:19:25,230 --> 00:19:27,892
They weren't laughing at you, honey.
They were laughing with you.

345
00:19:29,801 --> 00:19:33,168
What was there to laugh <i>with,</i> George?

346
00:19:33,272 --> 00:19:35,331
<i>[Ann]</i>
<i>I think you're overreacting, darling.</i>

347
00:19:35,440 --> 00:19:37,670
Don't tell me I'm overreacting.

348
00:19:37,776 --> 00:19:41,712
<i>Why am I so goddamn funny, George?</i>

349
00:19:41,813 --> 00:19:43,178
Harlan.

350
00:19:46,785 --> 00:19:49,754
Oh.
[Chuckles]

351
00:19:49,855 --> 00:19:51,755
I'm sorry. I must be overtired.

352
00:19:51,857 --> 00:19:54,621
It's probably just battle fatigue, sir.

353
00:19:56,261 --> 00:19:59,059
Sorry about that, Georgie boy.

354
00:20:04,002 --> 00:20:06,937
[Line Ringing]

355
00:20:07,039 --> 00:20:09,599
[Woman]
Hello? Who is this?

356
00:20:09,708 --> 00:20:14,509
Nicky, is that you? Hello?

357
00:20:14,613 --> 00:20:17,104
[Dan] Oh, sweetie,
it's the middle of the damn night.

358
00:20:17,216 --> 00:20:19,116
- Just hang up.
- [Line Disconnects]

359
00:20:19,218 --> 00:20:21,186
- Dad, it's...
- [Dial Tone]

360
00:20:32,531 --> 00:20:34,499
<i>[Dog Barking In Distance]</i>

361
00:20:38,237 --> 00:20:40,137
<i>[Harlan]</i>
<i>Find anything interesting, George?</i>

362
00:20:40,239 --> 00:20:43,470
- No, sir. Good night, sir.
- Sit.

363
00:20:43,575 --> 00:20:45,099
- I've gotta go.
- <i>Sit.</i>

364
00:20:45,210 --> 00:20:47,178
Sit.

365
00:20:50,482 --> 00:20:53,246
You think of yourself as
the man of the family, don't ya?

366
00:20:53,352 --> 00:20:56,549
- My brother's older.
- <i>Robbie's... Well, let's just say...</i>

367
00:20:56,655 --> 00:20:59,783
that Robbie's not likely
to be the man in anyone's family.

368
00:21:01,760 --> 00:21:04,058
I'm gonna marry your mother.

369
00:21:04,162 --> 00:21:08,565
- I know.
- <i>That's going to make me the man of the family.</i>

370
00:21:09,868 --> 00:21:13,065
<i>[Dog Barking In Distance]</i>

371
00:21:13,171 --> 00:21:15,696
It's like dogs, see?

372
00:21:15,807 --> 00:21:19,800
In every pack,
there's a leader of the pack.

373
00:21:19,911 --> 00:21:22,937
You've been that dog for a while.

374
00:21:23,048 --> 00:21:25,141
Now, I'm going to be top dog.

375
00:21:26,885 --> 00:21:30,412
<i>And there's always the dog</i>
<i>that challenges the leader.</i>

376
00:21:32,024 --> 00:21:35,016
Things can get pretty nasty
till one of them wins.

377
00:21:36,928 --> 00:21:39,863
Son, you can fight me...

378
00:21:39,965 --> 00:21:45,301
but I guarantee you,
you're going to lose.

379
00:21:45,404 --> 00:21:47,872
<i>You understand?</i>

380
00:21:47,973 --> 00:21:51,033
Woof, sir.

381
00:21:51,143 --> 00:21:55,045
So, what's Harlan
gonna wear for the wedding?

382
00:21:55,147 --> 00:21:57,115
His uniform, I assume.

383
00:21:57,215 --> 00:21:59,877
- Does he sleep in that thing too?
- George!

384
00:22:01,620 --> 00:22:04,453
<i>Doesn't that just break your heart?</i>

385
00:22:04,556 --> 00:22:06,217
We should buy them something.

386
00:22:06,325 --> 00:22:08,555
<i>[Ann]</i>
<i>What a sweet idea.</i>

387
00:22:08,660 --> 00:22:11,356
- How much should we spend?
- How much did Harlan give you?

388
00:22:11,463 --> 00:22:14,523
- $500.
- Spend it all.

389
00:22:14,633 --> 00:22:16,794
Oh, I can't, George.
That money has to pay...

390
00:22:16,902 --> 00:22:19,029
for the caterers, the band, the flowers.

391
00:22:19,137 --> 00:22:21,332
<i>And before that,</i>
<i>there's a rehearsal dinner.</i>

392
00:22:21,440 --> 00:22:23,601
Look at them, Mother.

393
00:22:23,709 --> 00:22:27,645
<i>Are you telling me that you spent all the money</i>
<i>I gave you on a bunch of crippled kids?</i>

394
00:22:27,746 --> 00:22:30,237
I just couldn't help myself.

395
00:22:30,349 --> 00:22:33,182
And you should've seen them, darling.
They were so happy.

396
00:22:33,285 --> 00:22:38,348
I don't care if they were
shitting wedding bells.

397
00:22:38,457 --> 00:22:40,823
You stole 500 bucks from me.

398
00:22:40,926 --> 00:22:42,894
I didn't steal it, and I'll pay you back.

399
00:22:42,994 --> 00:22:46,054
How are you gonna do that?
How are you going to pay me back?

400
00:22:46,164 --> 00:22:48,394
- <i>How?</i>
- It was my idea.

401
00:22:48,500 --> 00:22:50,866
<i>[Ann]</i>
<i>It was not your idea.</i>

402
00:22:50,969 --> 00:22:53,597
I bet it was your idea, you little turd.

403
00:22:53,705 --> 00:22:57,197
<i>It was my idea, and don't call him that.</i>

404
00:22:57,309 --> 00:23:00,836
I'll call him any damn thing I wanna call him.
Now, give me back that necklace.

405
00:23:00,946 --> 00:23:02,709
- What are you talking about?
- The one you're wearing.

406
00:23:02,814 --> 00:23:04,748
The pearl necklace I gave you.
Give it to me.

407
00:23:04,850 --> 00:23:07,944
- Why?
- I'm returning it for the money you owe me.
Give it to me.

408
00:23:08,053 --> 00:23:09,543
I will not.

409
00:23:09,654 --> 00:23:13,055
- Give me that goddamn necklace!
Give me those goddamn pearls!
- Oh!

410
00:23:13,158 --> 00:23:15,149
- <i>[George] Leave her alone!</i>
- Come here!

411
00:23:15,260 --> 00:23:17,820
- [Screams]
- Give me those damn pearls!
You hear me, woman?

412
00:23:17,929 --> 00:23:22,161
- Leave her alone!
- I order you to give me those pearls right now!

413
00:23:23,668 --> 00:23:26,762
<i>Damn it, stop! You stop!</i>

414
00:23:26,872 --> 00:23:29,670
<i>If you touch my boy again...</i>

415
00:23:29,775 --> 00:23:33,142
you miserable son of a bitch,
I will kill you!

416
00:23:35,380 --> 00:23:37,075
- <i>[Grunts Loudly]</i>
- Oh...

417
00:23:37,182 --> 00:23:39,412
[Groans]

418
00:23:39,518 --> 00:23:42,612
<i># #[Rock On Speakers]</i>

419
00:23:42,721 --> 00:23:45,519
You jumped on his back?

420
00:23:45,624 --> 00:23:49,116
Your brother was so brave.

421
00:23:49,227 --> 00:23:51,127
Are we going home now?

422
00:23:51,229 --> 00:23:54,426
- You know we can't do that.
- Why not?

423
00:23:54,533 --> 00:23:57,627
- Because your father doesn't love me.
- Why not?

424
00:23:57,736 --> 00:24:01,069
Well, you'll have
to ask him that yourself.

425
00:24:01,173 --> 00:24:03,733
- We don't have any money left, do we?
- <i>We have plenty of money.</i>

426
00:24:03,842 --> 00:24:06,777
How much?

427
00:24:06,878 --> 00:24:09,745
Enough to keep us until I find someone.

428
00:24:09,848 --> 00:24:12,408
- You mean, like, a husband?
- <i>And a father.</i>

429
00:24:12,517 --> 00:24:15,850
Does it worry you that the last one
you picked turned out to be a total psycho?

430
00:24:15,954 --> 00:24:19,253
So, where's the next spot on the map?

431
00:24:19,357 --> 00:24:21,689
<i>Where is that map?</i>

432
00:24:25,263 --> 00:24:27,197
What's this?

433
00:24:27,299 --> 00:24:30,632
- It's mine.
- Be careful, George.

434
00:24:33,405 --> 00:24:35,305
Does he ever write you back?

