and live with him.

666
00:38:24,935 --> 00:38:27,699
I'm not gonna let you do that, George.

667
00:38:27,805 --> 00:38:30,774
<i>We can't stay here anymore.</i>
<i>We have no money.</i>

668
00:38:33,277 --> 00:38:37,407
Darling, your father...

669
00:38:38,716 --> 00:38:40,616
He doesn't want you.

670
00:38:40,718 --> 00:38:43,414
- He does too want me.
- <i>You don't know him like I do.</i>

671
00:38:43,521 --> 00:38:47,150
I know him better than you do, and I know
that he'll take me back in a minute.

672
00:38:47,258 --> 00:38:51,024
George. I know
this has been hard for you.

673
00:38:51,128 --> 00:38:54,495
But things will change soon, I promise.

674
00:38:54,598 --> 00:38:58,762
How? How will they change?

675
00:38:58,869 --> 00:39:02,270
I'm going dancing tonight
with Mr. Currell.

676
00:39:04,408 --> 00:39:08,242
[Sighs]
Mom. Listen.

677
00:39:11,115 --> 00:39:13,379
Charlie Currell is not interested in you.

678
00:39:13,484 --> 00:39:17,250
- You know that for a fact, do you?
- Yeah. Everybody knows that.

679
00:39:17,355 --> 00:39:21,155
That girl he was with today
is closer to my age than she is to yours.

680
00:39:21,258 --> 00:39:24,056
Don't say anything you'll regret.

681
00:39:24,161 --> 00:39:29,497
You have two kids, for Christ's sake.
You're too old for him.

682
00:39:29,600 --> 00:39:31,158
Isn't it obvious?

683
00:39:32,737 --> 00:39:35,137
It is to everyone else.

684
00:39:39,877 --> 00:39:45,110
<i>[Woman] #It's such a cryin' shame</i>
<i>to play the numbers game #</i>

685
00:39:45,216 --> 00:39:50,483
<i># And barely know</i>
<i>the company you're keepin'#</i>

686
00:39:50,588 --> 00:39:53,079
<i># You can take the tears #</i>

687
00:39:53,190 --> 00:39:55,852
# Give me the golden years #

688
00:39:55,960 --> 00:40:01,159
#The smiles that I'll be reapin'
while I know each night I'm sleepin' #

689
00:40:01,265 --> 00:40:03,733
# I'll wake up to a friend #

690
00:40:03,834 --> 00:40:07,497
<i># And another happy end #</i>

691
00:40:09,240 --> 00:40:11,504
<i># Has begun #</i>

692
00:40:11,609 --> 00:40:16,546
#With my one and only ##

693
00:40:19,683 --> 00:40:22,618
- ## [Ends]
- [Applause]

694
00:40:24,288 --> 00:40:26,381
Thank you. Thank you, Tanya.
Isn't she great?

695
00:40:26,490 --> 00:40:30,950
<i>Folks, that was "My One and Only"hit.</i>

696
00:40:31,061 --> 00:40:33,655
- <i>[Laughter]</i>
- Hey. Give me time.

697
00:40:33,764 --> 00:40:36,562
Give me time.
One, two, three.

698
00:40:36,667 --> 00:40:40,000
<i># #[Resumes]</i>

699
00:40:47,845 --> 00:40:49,813
- Can I help you, ma'am?
- I'm meeting Mr. Currell.

700
00:40:49,914 --> 00:40:51,814
I don't believe Mr. Currell's party
is here yet, ma'am.

701
00:40:51,916 --> 00:40:53,850
But they usually head right up
to the Starlight Room.

702
00:40:53,951 --> 00:40:55,851
Thank you.
I'll wait for him in the bar.

703
00:40:55,953 --> 00:40:58,820
- <i># #[Continues]</i>
- <i>[Laughter, Chattering]</i>

704
00:41:00,391 --> 00:41:04,293
Hey, kid.
What you doin' here?

705
00:41:04,395 --> 00:41:06,295
We're living here now.
Didn't you get my postcards?

706
00:41:06,397 --> 00:41:08,422
Well, yeah, sure I got 'em.
But I've been on the road.

707
00:41:08,532 --> 00:41:11,899
You know how that is. Hey, Carl. Carl.
You remember my boy George.

708
00:41:12,002 --> 00:41:15,597
- Oh, sure, yeah. Hi. How are you?
- This here's Tanya, our singer.

709
00:41:15,706 --> 00:41:17,606
- Hi, cutie.
- And you know Nate.

710
00:41:17,708 --> 00:41:20,074
- Hey! How's it goin', George?
- It's okay.

711
00:41:20,177 --> 00:41:22,645
- All right.
- Hey, sit down. Sit down.

712
00:41:24,081 --> 00:41:26,549
- So where are you livin'?
- In an apartment on the South Side.

713
00:41:26,650 --> 00:41:29,813
- Yeah? Nice place?
- No, it's mostly working people.

714
00:41:29,920 --> 00:41:32,514
That must rankle your mother to no end.

715
00:41:32,623 --> 00:41:34,648
Imagine her livin' with the riffraff.

716
00:41:34,758 --> 00:41:37,625
- She's fine.
- Good.

717
00:41:37,728 --> 00:41:40,788
Hey, you want a Coke?

718
00:41:40,898 --> 00:41:42,695
- You got a Coke?
- Give the kid a Coke.

719
00:41:42,800 --> 00:41:46,668
- I don't want a Coke.
- What do you want?

720
00:41:50,441 --> 00:41:52,841
I want you to take me back
to New York with you.

721
00:41:52,943 --> 00:41:56,208
Take you back? Oh, man.

722
00:41:56,313 --> 00:41:58,144
Son, I'd like to do that.
I really would.

723
00:41:58,249 --> 00:42:01,082
But I'm on the road for, like, what,
five months at least.

724
00:42:01,185 --> 00:42:03,949
After this, we go straight to Cleveland.
And after Cleveland, it's...

725
00:42:04,054 --> 00:42:06,249
- Hey, Carl, what's after Cleveland?
- Chicago.

726
00:42:06,357 --> 00:42:08,257
- <i>Chicago.</i>
- Five weeks.

727
00:42:08,359 --> 00:42:10,418
Five weeks in Chicago.
And then, you know, who knows where?

728
00:42:10,528 --> 00:42:12,223
- Kansas City.
- Kansas City.

729
00:42:12,329 --> 00:42:14,729
- After that, Dallas.
- After that, Dallas. And Dallas...

730
00:42:14,832 --> 00:42:17,767
And you'd hate Dallas, George.
I gotta tell you. What's after Dallas?

731
00:42:17,868 --> 00:42:19,859
- Phoenix.
- Phoenix.

732
00:42:19,970 --> 00:42:22,905
Okay. Forget about it.
I wasn't being serious.

733
00:42:23,007 --> 00:42:26,170
I was just kidding anyways.
I'm gonna stay here.

734
00:42:26,277 --> 00:42:29,075
- So how you fixed for money?
- We're running out.

735
00:42:29,179 --> 00:42:32,740
Yeah? You know, I send your mother money
all the time. She sends it back to me.

736
00:42:32,850 --> 00:42:34,750
- She does?
- Yeah.

737
00:42:34,852 --> 00:42:36,717
So I stopped.
She got a job?

738
00:42:36,820 --> 00:42:39,755
Oh, man!
[Laughing]

739
00:42:39,857 --> 00:42:42,849
What was I thinkin'?
Can you imagine Ann gettin' a job?

740
00:42:42,960 --> 00:42:45,428
Your mother always thought
she was too good to work.

741
00:42:45,529 --> 00:42:47,963
I hate to be the one
to break it to you, kid...

742
00:42:48,065 --> 00:42:51,262
but your mother has got
delusions of grandeur.

743
00:42:51,368 --> 00:42:53,268
- No, she doesn't.
- Mm-hmm.

744
00:42:53,370 --> 00:42:57,704
She always figured she was some kind
of southern royalty, man, you know.

745
00:42:57,808 --> 00:43:00,800
But you gotta take it from me.
In the real world...

746
00:43:00,911 --> 00:43:02,936
class doesn't count for anything.

747
00:43:03,047 --> 00:43:06,107
If it ain't in the bank,
it ain't anywhere.

748
00:43:13,490 --> 00:43:17,654
Let me see if I got some...
Hey, Carl.

749
00:43:19,263 --> 00:43:21,163
- You got any money on you?
- No.

750
00:43:21,265 --> 00:43:24,166
Don't bullshit me, man.
Come on. Give me $100. It's for the kid.

751
00:43:24,268 --> 00:43:27,396
- I got some.
- I don't want your money.

752
00:43:27,504 --> 00:43:30,064
Wait. Hey, hey.
Come on, now. Don't be stupid, kid.

753
00:43:30,174 --> 00:43:33,109
Take the money.
Don't be like your mother. Take it...

754
00:43:33,210 --> 00:43:35,678
till she finds some other guy
to pay her way.

755
00:43:35,779 --> 00:43:38,077
Did you ever love her?

756
00:43:38,182 --> 00:43:40,776
Your mom? Yeah.

757
00:43:40,884 --> 00:43:42,852
I loved her a lot.

758
00:43:45,222 --> 00:43:49,022
- You ever love me?
- You're up in five!

759
00:43:49,126 --> 00:43:52,254
- I better go.
- Wait, wait.

760
00:43:52,363 --> 00:43:55,821
I still love you, pal.
You know, it's just...

761
00:43:55,933 --> 00:43:58,800
I mean, with my life
on the road and all...

762
00:43:58,902 --> 00:44:00,836
I was never cut out to be a father.

763
00:44:00,938 --> 00:44:04,704
Just-Just like your mom
was never cut out to be a mother.

764
00:44:04,808 --> 00:44:06,708
Yeah, well, at least she tries.

765
00:44:08,412 --> 00:44:10,471
Yeah, she does try.

766
00:44:11,982 --> 00:44:15,349
She loves you, kid.
Don't ever forget that.

767
00:44:15,452 --> 00:44:18,285
See ya.

768
00:44:19,456 --> 00:44:21,356
Hey.

769
00:44:21,458 --> 00:44:23,824
[Clicks Tongue]
I'll see you, George.

770
00:44:29,033 --> 00:44:31,001
I'll see you around.

771
00:44:33,070 --> 00:44:35,061
You owe me a hundred, Dan.

772
00:44:36,640 --> 00:44:38,608
<i># #[Piano]</i>

773
00:44:44,348 --> 00:44:46,316
- Thank you.
- Ma'am.

774
00:45:01,632 --> 00:45:04,760
<i>Paging Mr. Foster.</i>
<i>There's a call here for Mr. Foster.</i>

775
00:45:04,868 --> 00:45:07,666
<i>Call for Mr. Foster at reception.</i>

776
00:45:12,643 --> 00:45:16,204
[Chattering, Laughing]

777
00:45:24,922 --> 00:45:28,858
When your old friend shows up, you can
dance with her once, but that's all.

778
00:45:28,959 --> 00:45:32,122
I doubt she'll even come, doll.
She's got kids to take care of.

779
00:45:32,229 --> 00:45:34,891
- <i>Well, then it's probably past her bedtime.</i>
- <i>You...</i>

780
00:45:34,998 --> 00:45:37,865
[Elevator Bell Dings]

781
00:45:39,169 --> 00:45:42,297
- <i>[Man] All aboard!</i>
- <i>[Man #2] We can all get in.</i>

782
00:45:57,654 --> 00:45:59,747
<i>[Bartender]</i>
<i>Martini? Certainly, ma'am.</i>

783
00:46:21,311 --> 00:46:24,246
- Hi, there. I'm Ann.
- Hi.

784
00:46:24,348 --> 00:46:26,748
I'm Frank.

785
00:46:26,850 --> 00:46:28,875
- Hello, Frank.
- Hello.

786
00:46:28,986 --> 00:46:32,683
I hope you don't mind me
coming over here to talk to you.

787
00:46:32,790 --> 00:46:34,758
Not at all, no.

788
00:46:37,161 --> 00:46:39,789
I don't normally do this.

789
00:46:39,897 --> 00:46:41,990
- Ma'am.
- Don't you?

790
00:46:44,268 --> 00:46:48,466
I'm a little lonely tonight.
Are you alone too?

791
00:46:50,340 --> 00:46:52,308
Yeah, I'm-I'm alone.

792
00:46:53,844 --> 00:46:57,940
- From out of town?
- Well, originally, yeah.

793
00:46:58,048 --> 00:47:02,485
So you're staying here at the hotel?

794
00:47:02,586 --> 00:47:05,453
Well, actually, Ann,
l-I work at the hotel.

795
00:47:05,556 --> 00:47:08,719
Oh, do you?
Well, what do you do?

796
00:47:11,695 --> 00:47:14,391
[Sighs]
I'm a detective.

797
00:47:14,498 --> 00:47:16,989
And I'm arresting you for solicitation.

798
00:47:18,602 --> 00:47:21,196
- Prostitution.
- [Laughing]

799
00:47:25,042 --> 00:47:27,977
You had me going there, Frank.

800
00:47:28,078 --> 00:47:30,478
I'm not kidding, ma'am.

801
00:47:31,982 --> 00:47:33,882
- [Chuckles]
- Now, listen, you have a choice here.

802
00:47:33,984 --> 00:47:36,009
I can either handcuff you
right here at the bar...

803
00:47:36,119 --> 00:47:39,486
which would be very unpleasant for you,
for me and for the hotel...

804
00:47:39,590 --> 00:47:45,153
or you can walk quietly with me to the back
while we wait for a police officer.

805
00:47:47,064 --> 00:47:50,898
All right. Come on, doll.

806
00:47:59,042 --> 00:48:01,237
- [Line Ringing]
- It's ringing.

807
00:48:03,881 --> 00:48:05,781
- <i># #[Up-tempo Jazz]</i>
- <i>[Phone Ringing]</i>

808
00:48:05,883 --> 00:48:09,284
'Cause you know how he starts
playing something, and it's totally wrong.

809
00:48:09,386 --> 00:48:13,015
- <i>[Ringing Continues]</i>
- Hello.

810
00:48:13,123 --> 00:48:14,818
Yeah. Who is it?

811
00:48:14,925 --> 00:48:17,393
Hey, hey, hey! Hey, y'all, keep it down,
for Christ's sake.

812
00:48:17,494 --> 00:48:19,689
- Who is it, Dan? Another girlfriend?
- Give me that thing.

813
00:48:19,796 --> 00:48:22,128
[Tanya]
Hello? H...

814
00:48:22,232 --> 00:48:25,224
[Dan] Come on, baby.
Give me that phone. Stop fooling around.

815
00:48:25,335 --> 00:48:29,533
Yeah. Hello? Who is it?

816
00:48:29,640 --> 00:48:31,540
- Oh, well.
- <i>[Replaces Handset In Cradle]</i>

817
00:48:31,642 --> 00:48:33,610
[Line Disconnects]

818
00:48:34,645 --> 00:48:36,545
There's no one there.

819
00:48:57,501 --> 00:49:00,299
- [Chattering]
- Come on.

820
00:49:00,404 --> 00:49:02,372
- Come on.
- No, wait!

821
00:49:04,875 --> 00:49:06,934
Thank you.

822
00:49:07,044 --> 00:49:09,012
I'd like to, um...

823
00:49:11,682 --> 00:49:13,775
I need to explain.

824
00:49:13,884 --> 00:49:16,148
You don't need to explain anything to me.

825
00:49:16,253 --> 00:49:18,221
You just need to get home.

826
00:49:20,424 --> 00:49:22,392
Thank you.

827
00:49:27,097 --> 00:49:30,396
Well, good night.

828
00:49:30,500 --> 00:49:32,400
Well, morning.
[Chuckles]

829
00:49:32,502 --> 00:49:34,436
Yeah.

830
00:49:34,538 --> 00:49:36,506
Thank you.

831
00:49:41,011 --> 00:49:43,377
Oh, uh, Bud?

832
00:49:45,749 --> 00:49:49,947
I would really appreciate it
if this didn't get around.

833
00:49:50,053 --> 00:49:51,953
If what didn't get around, ma'am?

834
00:49:52,055 --> 00:49:54,319
[Chuckles]

835
00:49:54,424 --> 00:49:57,484
You're the most beautiful woman
I ever saw, Mrs. Devereaux.

836
00:50:15,645 --> 00:50:17,772
You take care of yourself, ma'am.

837
00:50:25,088 --> 00:50:27,750
Bud?

838
00:50:27,858 --> 00:50:32,056
You're the first real gentleman
I've met since I left New York.

839
00:50:45,308 --> 00:50:48,937
- Where were you?
- Car broke down.

840
00:50:49,046 --> 00:50:51,139
- What was wrong with it?
- How should I know?

841
00:50:51,248 --> 00:50:54,308
Bud fixed it. Ask him.
Where's your brother?

842
00:50:54,418 --> 00:50:57,945
- He had rehearsal.
- Oh. Well, get your things together.

843
00:50:58,055 --> 00:51:00,853
His too. We're leaving.

844
00:51:00,957 --> 00:51:03,357
We're not goin' back to Dad now, are we?

845
00:51:04,895 --> 00:51:07,557
You saw him, didn't you?

846
00:51:07,664 --> 00:51:10,565
Yeah, I saw him, and he's a shit.

847
00:51:10,667 --> 00:51:13,795
Don't talk like that about your father.

848
00:51:13,904 --> 00:51:16,429
You'll regret it one day.

849
00:51:16,540 --> 00:51:19,441
What do you care? Hmm?

850
00:51:19,543 --> 00:51:22,637
It's pretty obvious that you're not
thinking about him these days.

851
00:51:24,414 --> 00:51:27,008
I have been loyal to your father...

852
00:51:27,117 --> 00:51:30,280
since the day I met him...

853
00:51:30,387 --> 00:51:33,720
which is something no one would make
the mistake of saying about him.

854
00:51:33,824 --> 00:51:35,985
That's what I said. He's a shit.

855
00:51:36,093 --> 00:51:39,460
Your father adores you.

856
00:51:39,563 --> 00:51:40,996
Right.

857
00:51:47,904 --> 00:51:50,134
When you were two...

858
00:51:50,240 --> 00:51:52,140
or maybe three years old...

859
00:51:52,242 --> 00:51:54,335
you came down with something awful.

860
00:51:54,444 --> 00:51:56,344
Like an earache or something.

861
00:51:56,446 --> 00:51:58,346
Well, whatever it was, you were crying...

862
00:51:58,448 --> 00:52:01,747
and nothin' anybody did
could make you stop.

863
00:52:01,852 --> 00:52:05,686
Until your father came into your room...

864
00:52:05,789 --> 00:52:09,919
sat down on your bed,
and started playing his clarinet.

865
00:52:11,328 --> 00:52:13,592
- He did?
- Mm-hmm.

866
00:52:13,697 --> 00:52:17,155
And whenever he would stop,
you would just start crying again.

867
00:52:17,267 --> 00:52:21,966
So he just kept on playing nonstop
for what felt like days.

868
00:52:22,072 --> 00:52:24,939
What happened?

869
00:52:25,041 --> 00:52:27,009
You got better.

870
00:52:28,912 --> 00:52:31,210
That's the biggest bunch of crap
I've ever heard.

871
00:52:34,684 --> 00:52:38,780
There are some things
that you are too young to understand.

872
00:52:38,889 --> 00:52:41,289
Such as?

873
00:52:41,391 --> 00:52:45,725
Such as you're not the only one
who gets lonely around here.

874
00:52:47,197 --> 00:52:49,165
<i>[Keys Jingling]</i>

875
00:52:59,576 --> 00:53:01,544
George.

876
00:53:05,248 --> 00:53:07,341
- You guys leavin'?
- Yeah.

877
00:53:07,450 --> 00:53:11,147
They'll probably rent your apartment out
to some loser.

878
00:53:11,254 --> 00:53:13,586
Probably will.

879
00:53:15,759 --> 00:53:17,386
George, we should get going.

880
00:53:20,230 --> 00:53:22,721
I'll see you around.

881
00:53:22,832 --> 00:53:25,528
Yeah. Yeah, I'll see you around.

882
00:53:40,317 --> 00:53:43,115
<i>[Starts Engine]</i>

883
00:53:47,524 --> 00:53:51,085
[Ann]
George. Mirror.

884
00:53:51,194 --> 00:53:52,991
Bye.

885
00:53:53,096 --> 00:53:54,961
<i>[Robbie]</i>
<i>George, this is ridiculous.</i>

886
00:53:55,065 --> 00:53:56,965
Is it a family tragedy, boys?

887
00:53:57,067 --> 00:53:59,126
We're going to our Aunt Hope's
in St. Louis.

888
00:53:59,236 --> 00:54:01,136
That counts as a tragedy.

889
00:54:01,238 --> 00:54:03,536
Okay, everybody, let's, uh...
let's take five.

890
00:54:07,677 --> 00:54:11,010
- <i>[Ann] Thank you.</i>
- The doctors have tried everything.

891
00:54:12,515 --> 00:54:15,973
Eat up, boys. Breakfast is
the most important meal of the day.

892
00:54:16,086 --> 00:54:18,281
Especially when it's your only meal
of the day.

893
00:54:20,190 --> 00:54:22,317
You sure Aunt Hope has room for us all?

894
00:54:22,425 --> 00:54:26,919
Your Aunt Hope and Uncle Tom
have a comfortable if modest home.

895
00:54:27,030 --> 00:54:28,930
<i>Uncle Tom's Cabin. How appropriate.</i>

896
00:54:29,032 --> 00:54:32,126
- Aunt Hope... the woman that God forgot.
- [Chuckles]

897
00:54:32,235 --> 00:54:34,601
Your Aunt Hope is a good person.

898
00:54:34,704 --> 00:54:36,797
What happened,
did you run out of ex-boyfriends?

899
00:54:36,906 --> 00:54:39,704
<i>[Robbie] You did say you'd never</i>
<i>go back there, remember?</i>

900
00:54:39,809 --> 00:54:43,404
Well, I said a lot of things
that don't mean much now.

901
00:54:43,513 --> 00:54:47,779
- Why are we going there if you hate her so much?
- I love my sister, George.

902
00:54:47,884 --> 00:54:51,718
It's being near her that I hate.

903
00:54:51,821 --> 00:54:56,019
Things will turn our way soon.
Now eat your food.

904
00:55:02,666 --> 00:55:04,566
Looking for somebody?

905
00:55:06,536 --> 00:55:08,595
Yeah. Ann Devereaux.

906
00:55:10,607 --> 00:55:12,199
They left yesterday.

907
00:55:16,012 --> 00:55:17,673
She say where they were going?

908
00:55:19,849 --> 00:55:22,682
- Who wants to know?
- Her husband.

909
00:55:24,688 --> 00:55:27,156
Your wife's a beautiful woman.

910
00:55:27,257 --> 00:55:29,350
<i>She's got a lot of class.</i>

911
00:55:30,960 --> 00:55:34,123
Yeah, well, I guess
I knew that before you did.

912
00:55:36,366 --> 00:55:39,699
They're heading west.
Said something about her sister.

913
00:55:40,904 --> 00:55:43,873
- Thanks, pal.
- <i>Don't mention it.</i>

914
00:55:47,243 --> 00:55:49,905
<i>[George Narrating] My mother always said</i>
<i>she'd have to be desperate...</i>

915
00:55:50,013 --> 00:55:51,981
<i>to go to her sister's in St. Louis.</i>

916
00:55:52,082 --> 00:55:53,982
<i>So I guess we were officially desperate.</i>

917
00:55:54,084 --> 00:55:57,850
- Tom?
- Ann? Is that you?

918
00:55:57,954 --> 00:55:59,888
Hi, Tom!

919
00:55:59,989 --> 00:56:01,957
Pull up around the back.

920
00:56:03,993 --> 00:56:07,019
- Where'd you get that car?
- <i>[Ann Laughs]</i>

921
00:56:10,100 --> 00:56:12,159
Hey, Hope, your crazy sister.

922
00:56:14,204 --> 00:56:16,468
Robbie, you can have
half your Uncle Tom's pork chop.

923
00:56:16,573 --> 00:56:18,564
Give him the meaty half, Tom.

924
00:56:18,675 --> 00:56:20,609
- All right.
- And George can have my mashed potatoes.

925
00:56:20,710 --> 00:56:22,735
- I don't want your mashed potatoes, Aunt Hope.
- Of course you do.

926
00:56:22,846 --> 00:56:24,746
You're our guests,
and we're happy to feed you...

927
00:56:24,848 --> 00:56:28,409
- even if it is with the food off our own plates.
- Thank your Aunt Hope, George.

928
00:56:28,518 --> 00:56:32,045
<i>No need to thank me. You're family.</i>
<i>Good Christian people help their families...</i>

929
00:56:32,155 --> 00:56:34,749
even when they do show up hungry
and without a word of warning.

930
00:56:34,858 --> 00:56:36,917
Well, especially then.

931
00:56:37,026 --> 00:56:40,462
So, from what you say, it sounds like you don't
even know yourselves where you're going.

932
00:56:40,563 --> 00:56:42,724
The boys and I are on an adventure.

933
00:56:42,832 --> 00:56:45,801
Oh.
[Chuckles]

934
00:56:45,902 --> 00:56:50,134
I only wish Father were here to see where
his little darling is having supper tonight.

935
00:56:50,240 --> 00:56:53,437
Apple doesn't fall far
from the tree after all, does it?

936
00:56:53,543 --> 00:56:55,670
Guess not.
